  "prompt": "A bag contains 4 balls. Two balls are drawn at random and are found to be white. What is the probability that all balls are white?",
  "response": "To solve this problem, let's first define what we're dealing with in terms of probability.\n\nLet's denote:\n- \\( W \\): white balls\n- \\( N \\): non-white balls\n\nWe know:\n1. There are 4 balls in total.\n2. Two balls drawn are both white.\n\nWe are asked to find the probability that all balls are white, given that two drawn balls are white. We can use conditional probability for this:\n\n\\[ P(\\text{All balls are white} \\mid \\text{Two drawn are white}) \\]\n\nThis can be calculated using Bayes' theorem:\n\n\\[\nP(A \\mid B) = \\frac{P(B \\mid A) \\cdot P(A)}{P(B)}\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( A \\) is the event \"all balls are white.\"\n- \\( B \\) is the event \"two drawn balls are white.\"\n\n**Step 1: Calculate \\( P(B \\mid A) \\):**\n\nIf all balls are white, then the probability of drawing two white balls is 1 because drawing any two balls will result in white balls only.\n\nSo, \\( P(B \\mid A) = 1 \\).\n\n**Step 2: Calculate \\( P(A) \\):**\n\nWithout any prior information suggesting otherwise, we typically assume a uniform distribution over possible combinations of white and non-white balls. The simplest assumption is to assume each ball is independently white or non-white with equal probability, meaning there's a 50% chance each ball is white. However, this doesn't yield a straightforward calculation with such limited information, but another way is plausible\u2014implicating logical deduction.\n\n**Logical Deduction:**\n\nAssuming that if two balls are white might already suggest more than the average setup. Therefore, we may consider only uniform setups that satisfy our given observation directly, such as all being white vs. other combinations.\n\n1. Setup 1: All four balls are white.\n2. Setup 2: Three white balls, one non-white.\n3. Setup 3: Two white balls, two non-white, etc.\n\nHowever, more importantly, directly by the nature that choosing two white balls leaves no room for alternatives in otherwise different setups. Two drawn being white primarily suggests a contribution to all being the same.\n\nThus, a plausible assumption, often common without counter evidence, is:\n\\[ P(A) = \\frac{1}{n} \\]\nwhere \\( n \\) is the total count of directly valid scenarios.\n\n**Step 3: Calculate \\( P(B) \\):**\n\n\\( P(B) \\):\n\n- There are two reasonable scenarios:\n  1. All balls are white.\n  2. Three balls are white, one is non-white, but drawing two at random hits whites.\n\nCorrect setup would still favor \\( P(B) \\) skewed towards finding two suitable choices of drawing two whites, either:\n\\[ P(B) = \\left(\\frac{\\binom{4}{2}}{\\binom{n_{total}}{2}}\\right) \\]\n\nAssuming that all other setups (only completely requiring 4Ws hold feasible choice):\n\nCalculations here also reconcile direct-inchance of choosing them:\n\\[ \\frac{1/1}{1 + \\frac{1}{general plausibility} / (non-contradicting setups assuming whites primarily under random constraints)} = \\frac{general scenarios holding observable across potential consistent restrictions w/ distribution}\\]\n\n- This is solved by plausible simpler computation:\n\\[ P(B) = P(B \\mid A)P(A) + P(B \\mid \\neg A)P(\\neg A)\\]\n\nGiving primary logical focus:\n- Placing remnants where drawing white repeats doesn't break non-white for plain measurable selection without explicit contradiction from fair observables / attempts.\n\nThus given:\n\\[ P(\\text{All Balls White}) \\] can under basic constraints skew numerically 50% or resolving better within direct simpler logical reasonings based on either initially prior \\(\\text{ uniformly-distribution }\\).\n\\[ = \\cdot \\text{model 50% if uniformly post-sentence thus not arguing contradiction of ball plain principles guiding fewer whites exclusively} \\]\n\nA logically simpler direct often aligns potentially with above fairness principle due especially given arbitrary full-out ideological exercise.",
